Pennsylvania
Tennessee
Virginia
West Virginia

The update mentions the importance of this tick for human and animal health. "The [longhorned] tick can reproduce parthenogenetically (without a male); as such, a single fed female tick can create a population. It is also a known/suspected vector of several viral, bacterial, and protozoan agents of livestock and human diseases. This 3-host tick can spread pathogens among a diverse host range, on which it feeds side-by-side with other tick species."

The report above indicates that this is the 1st time that _H. punctata_ has been found in the USA, but that both it and the Asian longhorned tick have been present in Block Island, Rhode Island for several years and found in specimens collected from 2010 onward. Although these ticks can cause adverse health effects on the livestock on which they feed due to loss of blood, so far none of the pathogens that they transmit in other countries have been found in the USA. - Mod.TY

